\\u003cBR\\u003eHong, Liang \\u003cBR\\u003eLi, Chenliang \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003eSection \\u003cSTRONG\\u003eEditors in Library and Information Science:\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e \\u003cBR\\u003eAn, Lu \\u003cBR\\u003eJiang, Tingting \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003eSection \\u003cSTRONG\\u003eEditors in Business and Management:\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e \\u003cBR\\u003eWu, Jiang \\u003cBR\\u003eSun, Yongqiang \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eDeputy Editor\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eXu, Jie \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eManaging Editor\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eDong, Ke \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eEditorial Office\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eDing, Nian\\u003cBR\\u003eHuang, Haiying \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eContact\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eSchool of Information Management\\u003cBR\\u003eWuhan University\\u003cBR\\u003e299 Bayi Rd., Wuhan, Hubei, P.R. China\\u003cBR\\u003ePostal Code: 430072\\u003cBR\\u003eEmail: \\u003cA href=\\\"mailto:dim@whu.edu.cn\\\"\\u003edim@whu.edu.cn\\u003c/A\\u003e \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003ePublisher\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eDe Gruyter Poland\\u003cBR\\u003eBogumi\u0142a Zuga 32A Str.\\u003cBR\\u003e01-811 Warsaw, Poland\\u003cBR\\u003eT: +48 22 701 50 15 \\u003c/P\\u003e\"},{\"type\":\"submission\",\"language\":\"English\",\"textformat\":null,\"content\":\"\\u003cDIV align=justify\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003eDIM encourages submissions which are able to advance the knowledge and practice on data-driven information management, including original research papers, literature reviews, case studies\uff0csurveys, positioning papers and editorials. As a peer-reviewed academic journal, DIM will present 20 research papers in each volume.\\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cA href=\\\"https://content.sciendo.com/supplemental/journals/dim/dim-overview.xml/Template.pdf\\\"\\u003eArticle Template\\u003c/A\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003cA href=\\\"https://content.sciendo.com/supplemental/journals/dim/dim-overview.xml/Latex_Template.zip\\\"\\u003eLatex Template\\u003c/A\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003cA href=\\\"https://content.sciendo.com/supplemental/journals/dim/dim-overview.xml/Template.doc\\\"\\u003eTemplate (Word)\\u003c/A\\u003e\\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eGuide for \\u003cEM\\u003eData and Information Management\\u003c/EM\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eWe welcome you to submit your manuscript to DIM. The instructions below are structured so that you can quickly and easily answer the following questions:\\u003cBR\\u003e1. Is my manuscript suitable for DIM? (see \\u003cU\\u003eAims and Scope\\u003c/U\\u003e)\\u003cBR\\u003e2. How do I format my manuscript for DIM? (see \\u003cU\\u003eManuscript File Formats\\u003c/U\\u003e)\\u003cBR\\u003e3. How do I submit my manuscript to DIM? (see \\u003cU\\u003eSubmission of Manuscripts\\u003c/U\\u003e)\\u003cBR\\u003e4. What is DIM\u2019s review system? (see \\u003cU\\u003eReview System\\u003c/U\\u003e)\\u003cBR\\u003e5. What is the Article publication charge? (see \\u003cU\\u003eCost\\u003c/U\\u003e) \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eManuscript File Formats\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eFor submission, acceptable manuscript file is expected to be Word or LaTeX documents. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eArticle types and length\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eDIM primarily publishes original research papers, literature reviews\uff0csurvey, empirical research papers\uff0ccase studies, editorial and positioning papers, among which editorial and positioning papers are expected to be about 1,000-2,000 words, and the rest over 6000 words. Hopefully, a research paper should be grounded in theory, include substantive evidence from the literature for critical points raised in the submission, and offer original and significant contribution to information science and big data. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003eIf a paper has already been published in a conference proceedings or a digital repository, the author(s) will need to revise the paper with approximately 30% different content and submit the manuscript to DIM under a new title. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eLanguage\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eMake spelling consistent with current editions of either Webster\u2019s Dictionary (Am. Eng.) or Oxford English Dictionary (Br. Eng.). \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eTitle page\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eThe title page should give a concise but informative title, the first and last names and other initials of all authors, as well as their affiliations (but not degrees).\\u003cBR\\u003eThe orders in which the contributors are listed should be agreed amongst the investigators, and should indicate that the first listed made the greatest contribution to the paper.\\u003cBR\\u003eFull contact details should be provided for the corresponding author. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eAbstract and keywords\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eThe abstract should be an unstructured narrative paragraph. It should be comprehensible to readers without their having read the paper, and abbreviations and reference citations within the abstract should be avoided. It should outline the purpose of the study, the basic procedures and the most important conclusions.\\u003cBR\\u003eKeywords, which may appear in the title, should be given below the abstract, each separated by a comma. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eIntroduction\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eThis should give a short, clear account of the background and reasons for undertaking the study by reference only to the pertinent literature. It should not be a review of all literature in the field but be limited to analysis of those aspects of previous work that raise questions that can be answered by the hypothesis addressed in the work being reported. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eAcknowledgements\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eThese should be brief, and should include sources of financial support, material (e.g. novel compounds, strains, etc.) not available commercially, personal assistance, advice from colleagues and gifts.\\u003cBR\\u003eAcknowledgements should be made only to those who have made a significant contribution to the study. Authors should submit to DIM written permission given by individuals named in this section. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eReferences\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eAuthors are responsible for the accuracy of the references. These may include published articles as well as those in press (but for these, state the name of the journal and enclose a copy of the manuscript).\\u003cBR\\u003eIn the text of the manuscript, references to the literature should be numbered consecutively and indicated by a superscript. Each reference should be numbered individually and listed at the end of the manuscript; DIM takes APA as its desired format style. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eTables\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eTables are useful for presentation of entire data-sets, and for results where little change between treatments occurs. (Figures here may show parallel lines that are difficult to distinguish from the overlapping symbols and error bars.)\\u003cBR\\u003eTables must supplement, not duplicate, the data in the text or Figures.\\u003cBR\\u003eTables should consist of at least two columns; columns should always have headings.\\u003cBR\\u003eThey should have a title and be numbered sequentially as Table 1, Table 2, etc. and cited sequentially in the text.\\u003cBR\\u003eTables should have a brief footnote that identifies all abbreviations used.\\u003cBR\\u003eReference to Table footnotes should be made by means of Arabic numeral as superscripts.\\u003cBR\\u003eThe data in the Tables should be consistent with those cited in the relevant places in the text. Check that totals add up correctly, that percentages have been calculated correctly and that the correct number of significant digits and decimal places are used. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eFigures\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eFigures are useful to highlight clear differences between treatment groups, where lines may diverge and symbols and errors bars do not overlap. (Tables here require concentrated attention to locate the superscript indices of statistical differences between columns or rows.)\\u003cBR\\u003eFigures must supplement, not duplicate, the data in the text or in Tables.\\u003cBR\\u003eIllustrations must clearly convey their message and be of high quality and sufficient size and clarity (especially lettering, arrows and data points) to be interpretable when reduced for publication.\\u003cBR\\u003eFigures should be given a title and numbered sequentially as Figure 1, Figure 2, etc. and cited (as Fig. 1, Fig. 2 etc.) sequentially in the text.\\u003cBR\\u003eThe position of Figures in the text should be referred to specifically in the paper but not embedded within the text.\\u003cBR\\u003eScale bars (not magnifications) should be provided on all photomicrographs. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003ePresentation of reproduced material\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eIf a Table or Figure has been published before, the authors must obtain written permission to reproduce the material in both print and electronic formats from the copyright owner and submit it with the manuscript.\\u003cBR\\u003ePrior written permission is also required for quotations, illustrations and other material taken from previously-published works not in the public domain. The original source should be cited in the Figure caption or Table footnote. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eAccepted file formats\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cUL\\u003e \\u003cLI\\u003eGraphical image files (.gif or tif(f)). \\u003c/LI\\u003e \\u003cLI\\u003eJPEG image files (.jpg or .jpeg). \\u003c/LI\\u003e \\u003cLI\\u003eMS Word documents (.doc or .docx). \\u003c/LI\\u003e \\u003cLI\\u003eLaTeX \\u003c/LI\\u003e\\u003c/UL\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eWord counts\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eFor all types of submission, word counts are inclusive of all textual matter (body of the manuscript, tables, captions, references and appendixes), not counting abstract and keywords. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eSubmission of Manuscripts\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eIf you have not done so already, please register for an account on our online submission and review system with De Gruyter (\\u003cA href=\\\"http://www.editorialmanager.com/dim\\\"\\u003ewww.editorialmanager.com/dim\\u003c/A\\u003e). \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eReview System\\u003c/STRONG\\u003e\\u003cBR\\u003eDIM adopts a double-blind peer review process to ensure quality. \\u003c/P\\u003e \\u003cP\\u003e\\u003cSTRONG\\u003eCost of Submission\\u003cBR\\u003e\\u003c/STRONG\\u003eDIM provides free access to its full-text articles as soon as they are available online. The open access fees (article-processing charges) are fully paid by Wuhan University, no charges are required from authors. \\u003c/P\\u003e\\u003c/DIV\\u003e\"},{\"type\":\"advantages\",\"language\":\"English\",\"textformat\":null,\"content\":\"\\u003cP align=justify\\u003eThe continuous increase in the volume and detail of data captured by organizations has produced an overwhelming flow of data in either structured or unstructured format. Managing and gaining insights and, more precisely, knowledge from the produced data is a great challenge and key to competitive advantage. The ability to cross-relate private information with information publically available on the Web, and data from social networks, and the analytics solutions to mining structured and unstructured data open a wide range of possibilities for organizations to understand the needs of their customers, and to optimize the use of resources. However, collecting data from various interrelated sources to provide \u201ccomplete\u201d data, accurate information, and so to generate actionable knowledge to achieve the added value of Big Data also poses challenges for government, academia, and industry. \\u003c/P\\u003e\"}]}],\"metrics\":\"\",\"pricing\":null,\"publicationFrequency\":{\"frequency\":\"4\",\"period\":\"YEAR\"},\"permissions\":null,\"contributors\":\"\",\"serial\":\"\",\"publishMonth\":\"03\",\"publishYear\":\"2020\",\"tableCount\":null,\"figureCount\":null,\"refCount\":null,\"keywords\":[],\"figures\":null,\"tables\":null,\"planPubDates\":[],\"epubLink\":null,\"pdfLink\":null,\"coverImage\":\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6009c72799b8105a15d5b3e3/cover-image.jpg\",\"coverImageOriginal\":\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6009c72799b8105a15d5b3e3/cover-image-original.jpg\",\"pdfFiles\":[],\"parentObjectId\":\"6009c72799b8105a15d5b3e3\",\"relatedTitles\":null,\"forAuthors\":null,\"nextPackageId\":null,\"prevPackageId\":\"6009c73c99b8105a15d5b3e4\",\"parentName\":\"Volume 4 (2020): Issue 1 (March 2020)\",\"grandParentId\":\"6005b04ae797941b18f23c66\",\"grandParentName\":\"Data and Information Management\",\"publisherName\":\"Sciendo\",\"publisherLocation\":null,\"nextMap\":{\"id\":{\"timestamp\":1610988471,\"date\":\"2021-01-18T16:47:51.000+00:00\"},\"doi\":null},\"prevMap\":{\"doi\":\"10.2478/dim-2020-0004\"},\"counter\":0,\"apaString\":\"Jansen,B.,Salminen,J. \\u0026 Jung,S.(2020).\\u003carticle-title\\u003eData-Driven Personas for Enhanced User Understanding: Combining Empathy with Rationality for Better Insights to Analytics\\u00