03e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eBraun\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eM.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2009\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eWebsite morphing\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eMarketing Science\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e28\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e2\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e202\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e223\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_023_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac23Aa\\\"\\u003eHauser, Urban, Liberali, \\u0026amp; Braun, 2009\\u003c/a\\u003e). \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_066_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac66Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eSrisuwan, P., \\u0026amp; Barnes, S. J. (2008). Predicting online channel use for an online and print magazine: A case study. \\u003citalic\\u003eInternet Research\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e18\\u003c/italic\\u003e(3), 266\u2013285.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSrisuwan\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eP.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eBarnes\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2008\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003ePredicting online channel use for an online and print magazine: A case study\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eInternet Research\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e18\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e3\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e266\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e285\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_066_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac66Aa\\\"\\u003eSrisuwan and Barnes (2008)\\u003c/a\\u003e highlight the need to know consumer preferences after the click, based on which the firm can prioritize activities that increase consumer enjoyment.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eData-driven Personas: Combining Analytics and Human Empathy\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_s_001_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b2Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3.1\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eOverview of APG\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eLeveraging these digital marketing use cases, we present research applying the concept of \u201cpersona as interface\u201d as the developmental foundation of APG, which is a system for the algorithmic creation of data-driven personas from a variety of online user data, such as Web, social media, or in-house customer data. In driving the advancement of persona conceptualization, development, and use, APG presents a multilayered (i.e., \u201cfull-stack\u201d) data integration concerning customers, audiences, or users. We demonstrate three levels of data access afforded by APG, which are (a) conceptual persona-level, (b) analytics-level, and (c) foundational customer/audience/user level. Personas-as-interfaces to online data systems, such as APG, address the common concerns voiced about traditionally created personas, most notably issues of data validity and practical value.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eRelated works (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ab4Aa\\\"\\u003