 not specifically addressed is the direct application of the data-driven persona to specific market use cases and explicitly articulating how data-driven personas integrate into this marketing merger of empathic personas and rational analytics. We begin addressing this gap by presenting the main benefits of APG in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"table\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b2b4Aa\\\"\\u003eTable 3\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003ctable-wrap id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b2b4Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003eTable 3\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003ccaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eMain Benefits of Automatically Generated Personas\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/caption\\u003e\\u003ctable rules=\\\"groups\\\"\\u003e\\u003cthead\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eAdvantage\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eDescription\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/thead\\u003e\\u003ctbody\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eSpeed\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonas can be created from social media data within hours. Traditional persona creation typically takes months\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAccuracy\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonas are based on latent behavioral patterns of the users. Traditional persona creation typically omits the measurement of behavioral patterns\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eFreshness\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonas are updated at a set interval (currently, each month). Traditionally created personas are not frequented updated due to time and cost\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eManipulability\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eThe persona profile template is easily modifiable enabling rapid experimentation. Traditionally generated personas are static and do not allow for easy experimentation\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eInactivity\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eThe persona profile serves as an interface to the underlying analytics information and user data. The personas are no longer a flat file serving as solely a data structure\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/tbody\\u003e\\u003c/table\\u003e\\u003c/table-wrap\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eSince APG obtains data directly from online platforms through APIs, this update process is completely automated. The fact we use these APIs also ensures that the privacy of individual users is kept intact. We retrieve bucketed information on user groups (e.g., Female 18\u201324, Brazil) and performance metrics (e.g., \u201cViews\u201d and \u201cClicks\u201d) that we computationally transform into persona representations. For a more detailed explanation, refer to \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_001_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ab1Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eAn, J., Kwak, H., \\u0026amp; Jansen, B. J. (2016). Validating Social Media Data for Automatic Persona Generation. \\u003citalic\\u003eProceedings of 13th ACS/IEEE International Conference on Computer Systems and Applications (AICCSA), 1\u20136\\u003c/italic\\u003e.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"confproc\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eAn\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eKwak\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eH.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJansen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2016\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eValidating Social Media Data for Automatic Persona Generation\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cconf-name\\u003eProceedings of 13th ACS/IEEE International Conference on Computer Systems and Applications (AICCSA)\\u003c/conf-name\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e1\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e6\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_001_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ab1Aa\\\"\\u003eAn, Kwak, and Jansen (2016)\\u003c/a\\u003e. Since the system is built upon a Web framework, rapid manipulation, and experimentation with different persona layouts become possible.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_s_002_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b3Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3.2\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eMethodology of APG\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eWe provide a concise overview of the APG system workflow that describes how user data for the persona profiles is retrieved, the manner the data are processed, and the process of creating the persona profiles. In general, APG produces personas from quantitative user data employing the following steps:\\n\\u003clist list-type=\\\"custom\\\"\\u003e\\u003clist-item\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e\u2013\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eStep 1\\u003c/bold\\u003e: Generate an interaction matrix (V) with items as columns (c), demographic user groups as rows (g), and the interaction amount of each group for each item as matrix elements\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/list-item\\u003e\\u003clist-item\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e\u2013\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eStep 2\\u003c/bold\\u003e: Use non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_037_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac37Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eLee, D. D., \\u0026amp; Seung, H. S. (1999). Learning the parts of objects by non-negative matrix factorization. \\u003citalic\\u003eNature\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e401\\u003c/italic\\u003e(6755), 788\u2013791.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eLee\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eD. D.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSeung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eH. S.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1999\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eLearning the parts of objects by non-negative matrix factorization\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eNature\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e401\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e6755\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e788\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e791\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_037_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac37Aa\\\"\\u003eLee \\u0026amp; Seung, 1999\\u003c/a\\u003e) to the interaction matrix to distinguish p latent item interaction behaviors (where p is a predetermined hyper-parameter signifying the number of personas).\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/list-item\\u003e\\u003clist-item\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e\u2013\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eStep 3\\u003c/bold\\u003e: Select the equivalent representative demographic attributes for each behavior by using weights from the NMF calculation.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/list-item\\u003e\\u003clist-item\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e\u2013\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eStep 4\\u003c/bold\\u003e: Augment p personas by adding the corresponding representative demographic groups with other information, such as name, picture, topics of interest, and so on.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/list-item\\u003e\\u003c/list\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eAfter attaining a grouped interaction matrix, the system applies NMF for classifying latent user interaction (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_005_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b3b4Aa\\\"\\u003eFigure 5\\u003c/a\\u003e). We first endeavored to identify segments through clustering, but this clustering approach did not work, as the social analytics data are aggregated. We, therefore, needed a method for de-aggregating the analytics. NMF is chiefly intended for decreasing the dimensionality of large datasets by discriminating latent factors (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_037_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac37Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eLee, D. D., \\u0026amp; Seung, H. S. (1999). Learning the parts of objects by non-negative matrix factorization. \\u003citalic\\u003eNature\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e401\\u003c/italic\\u003e(6755), 788\u2013791.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eLee\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eD. D.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSeung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eH. S.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1999\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eLearning the parts of objects by non-negative matrix factorization\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eNature\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e401\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e6755\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e788\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e791\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_037_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac37Aa\\\"\\u003eLee \\u0026amp; Seung, 1999\\u003c/a\\u003e). From this initial \u201cpersona,\u201d the APG system applies a process of improvement by adding a correct name, social media quotes, picture, and associated demographic characteristics (e.g., educational level, marital status, occupation, etc.) through querying the Facebook Marketing API. The result is a set of structural persona profiles representing the user population segments. The personas are presented to end users (i.e., the ones from the organization using the personas) through an online system operating on Flask,\\u003cfn id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fn_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b3b3b5Aa\\\" symbol=\\\"3\\\"\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cext-link xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\\" ext-link-type=\\\"uri\\\" xlink:href=\\\"http://flask.pocoo.org\\\"\\u003ehttp://flask.pocoo.org\\u003c/ext-link\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/fn\\u003e an open-source Python web framework. APG is a fully functional real system that is deployed with actual client organizations, with a demo available online.\\u003cfn id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fn_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b3b3b7Aa\\\" symbol=\\\"4\\\"\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cext-link xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\