ons.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe APG persona profiles contain the usual persona profile attributes, along with direct access provided to the underlying user data.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_s_003_s_002_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3.3.2\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eAnalytics Level (Probabilities, Percentages, and Weights)\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe APG persona profiles act as interactive interfaces to the underlying information leveraged to create the persona profiles. The information may somewhat vary among systems, but the analytics level reflects the specific measures and metrics generated using the foundational user data used to create the personas. In the APG system, the interactive personas profiles provide the affordances to the numerous analytics information through clickable icons in the persona interface. We discuss three examples.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eAs shown in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_008_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b4Aa\\\"\\u003eFigure 8\\u003c/a\\u003e, the APG system can display the entire user population percentage that a specific persona represents (this percentage is calculated from the Facebook API audience manager database). This particular analytic insight is valuable for organization decision-makers to decide the importance of developing or designing for a given persona, and it also assists in addressing the issue of whether or not the persona is valid (i.e., does the persona represent actual people).\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cfigure id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_008_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b4Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\" fig-type=\\\"figure\\\"\\u003e\\u003ch2\\u003eFigure 8\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cfigCaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eScreenshot of the percentage of the overall population epitomized by the persona.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/figCaption\\u003e\\u003cimg xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\\" xlink:href=\\\"graphic/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_008.jpg\\\" src=\\\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6005bbb5e797941b18f255fd/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_008.jpg?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Date=20211130T193832Z\\u0026amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Expires=18000\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Credential=AKIA6AP2G7AKDOZOEZ7H%2F20211130%2Feu-central-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Signature=ace5bc05404d3d1291c06a33ab335b2a0d0b75d97d30511cfb43e035c99255d2\\\" class=\\\"mw-100\\\"\\u003e\\u003c/img\\u003e\\u003c/figure\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eAPG gathers overall demographic information from the online analytics platform from which it is collecting the user data, which is typically gender, age grouping, and nationality of a user segment. Then, using these three attributes and the associated interests that are derived from the results of non-negative matrix factorization (NMF), APG leverages the Facebook API (with access to data from billions of users) to determine the probability of other demographic characteristics. The persona profiles provide access to these probabilities, which one example is shown in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_009_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b6Aa\\\"\\u003eFigure 9\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cfigure id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_009_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b6Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\" fig-type=\\\"figure\\\"\\u003e\\u003ch2\\u003eFigure 9\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cfigCaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eProbabilities of persona demographic characteristics (probability of marital status in this example).\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/figCaption\\u003e\\u003cimg xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\\" xlink:href=\\\"graphic/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_009.jpg\\\" src=\\\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6005bbb5e797941b18f255fd/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_009.jpg?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Date=20211130T193832Z\\u0026amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Expires=18000\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Credential=AKIA6AP2G7AKDOZOEZ7H%2F20211130%2Feu-central-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Signature=8dd2c6ad3495bbeaa2666672202f4ee314895a4d8e6a910db2fac789cdc3c03b\\\" class=\\\"mw-100\\\"\\u003e\\u003c/img\\u003e\\u003c/figure\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eAPG identifies the unique behavioral patterns, and it then associates these unique patterns, using latent factors, to one or more of the demographic groups. It assigns a weight to each of these demographic groups associated with a behavioral pattern based on the strength of the association to the pattern. These demographic weights provide many insights to the end user of the personas concerning both (a) the strength of behavior to this demographic and (b) the association of this behavior pattern with other demographic groups. Hence, APG provides access to these demographic group weights (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_010_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b8Aa\\\"\\u003eFigure 10\\u003c/a\\u003e), which helps address concerns of what actual users that the personas represent [6].\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cfigure id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_010_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b6b8Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\" fig-type=\\\"figure\\\"\\u003e\\u003ch2\\u003eFigure 10\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cfigCaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe weights generated by NMF for various demographic segments associated with one unique behavior pattern that used to generate the persona.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/figCaption\\u003e\\u003cimg xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\\" xlink:href=\\\"graphic/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_010.jpg\\\" src=\\\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6005bbb5e797941b18f255fd/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_010.jpg?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Date=20211130T193832Z\\u0026amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Expires=18000\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Credential=AKIA6AP2G7AKDOZOEZ7H%2F20211130%2Feu-central-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Signature=2ac20f462c61ea661a4c05f457f8a794beb33a9528e01be32e570cf62644fb7f\\\" class=\\\"mw-100\\\"\\u003e\\u003c/img\\u003e\\u003c/figure\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_s_003_s_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b7Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3.3.3\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eCustomer Level (Individual Data)\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eBy accessing the demographic meta-data output from the NMF process, the decision-maker can access the specific user level (i.e., individual or aggregate), as shown in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_011_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b7b3Aa\\\"\\u003eFigure 11\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cfigure id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_011_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b7b3Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\" fig-type=\\\"figure\\\"\\u003e\\u003ch2\\u003eFigure 11\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\u003cfigCaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe foundational user-level data from which the data-driven personas and analytics are generated. It is this numerical user data that be available in various formats, which are the foundational aspects of the data-driven persona presented in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"fig\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_fig_007_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b4b5b3Aa\\\"\\u003eFigures 7\u201310\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/figCaption\\u003e\\u003cimg xmlns:xlink=\\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\\" xlink:href=\\\"graphic/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_011.jpg\\\" src=\\\"https://sciendo-parsed-data-feed.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/6005bbb5e797941b18f255fd/j_dim-2020-0005_fig_011.jpg?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Date=20211130T193832Z\\u0026amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Expires=18000\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Credential=AKIA6AP2G7AKDOZOEZ7H%2F20211130%2Feu-central-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\\u0026amp;X-Amz-Signature=ebcb30b3ca26d451e552021fc542b0886eb6ee66d8a5c034f6452fe5ab6361af\\\" class=\\\"mw-100\\\"\\u003e\\u003c/img\\u003e\\u003c/figure\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_003_s_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b5Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e3.4\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eEvaluation of Personas in Digital Marketing Use Cases\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eHaving defined the digital marketing use cases and presented APG as a system for the generation of data-driven personas, we next evaluate their compatibility with different levels of data aggregation. We first explain the notion of data granularity, which is crucial for understanding the conceptual position presented here. There are various levels of data aggregation granularity, from the individual customer (i.e., 1-to-1 marketing) to the entire customer base (or overall market beyond it). Segments are located between the customer base and the individual customers, summarizing information about particular sub-groups of customers (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_013_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac13Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eClaycamp, H. J., \\u0026amp; Massy, W. F. (1968). A theory of market segmentation. \\u003citalic\\u003eJournal of Marketing Research\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e5\\u003c/italic\\u003e(4), 388\u2013394.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eClaycamp\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eH. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eMassy\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eW. F.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1968\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eA theory of market segmentation\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eJournal of Marketing Research\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e5\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e4\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e388\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e394\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_013_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac13Aa\\\"\\u003eClaycamp \\u0026amp; Massy, 1968\\u003c/a\\u003e). Individual data, therefore, refers to individual customers (e.g., \u201cPeter Jenkinson, 45-year-old male, Portland, Maine\u201d), aggregated data to a group (\u201cMale, 45\u201355 males, Portland, Maine\u201d). Personas are in between these two extremes, based on aggregated data but presented with individual attributes. In \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"table\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b5b3Aa\\\"\\u003eTable 4\\u003c/a\\u003e, we examine the digital marketing activities as potential use cases for personas to examine how online analytics data changes the applicability of personas from the decision-maker\u2019s point of view.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003ctable-wrap id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b2b5b3Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003eTable 4\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003ccaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe Suitability of Data Aggregation for Digital Marketing Use Cases.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/caption\\u003e\\u003ctable rules=\\\"groups\\\"\\u003e\\u003cthead\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eUse case\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eIndividual data\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eAggregated data\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eExample of Data-Driven Implementation in APG\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/thead\\u003e\\u003ctbody\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eChannel selection\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eX\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonas in APG are presented across multiple online platforms\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eTargeting\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eIndividual user data is available in APG and traceable from a given persona\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eIdentifying needs\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAPG automatically generates interest of the personas\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eMessage creation\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAPG offers functionality to test whether or not a message will resonate with a set of personas\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eBudget allocation\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAs of this date, functionality not implemented in APG\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eDynamic pricing\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAs of this date, functionality not implemented in APG\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eRecommendations\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAPG offers analysis features for product recommendations for personas\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonalization\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ex\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"/\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eIndividual user data is available in APG and traceable from a given persona\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/tbody\\u003e\\u003c/table\\u003e\\u003ctable-wrap-foot\\u003e\\u003cfn-group\\u003e\\u003cfn\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003e\\u003citalic\\u003eNote:\\u003c/italic\\u003e\\u003c/bold\\u003e For each activity, decision-makers use some form of data. When discussing personas\u2019 usefulness, we are actually asking which form of data representation is useful in which use case.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/fn\\u003e\\u003c/fn-group\\u003e\\u003c/table-wrap-foot\\u003e\\u003c/table-wrap\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eIn ad targeting, individual-level information is typically preferred (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_008_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ab8Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eBlattberg, R. C., \\u0026amp; Deighton, J. (1991). Interactive marketing: Exploiting the age of addressability. \\u003citalic\\u003eSloan Management Review, 33\\u003c/italic\\u003e(1), 5\u201315.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eBlattberg\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eR. C.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eDeighton\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1991\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eInteractive marketing: Exploiting the age of addressability\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eSloan Management Review\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e33\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e1\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e5\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e15\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_008_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ab8Aa\\\"\\u003eBlattberg \\u0026amp; Deighton, 1991\\u003c/a\\u003e). A low level of aggregation is desirable because match-making efficiency increases with the available information. If marketers know more about individual preferences, they can match the right products with the right consumers more efficiently. As noted by \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_033_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac33Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eKiani, G. R. (1998). Marketing opportunities in the digital world. \\u003citalic\\u003eInternet Research\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e8\\u003c/italic\\u003e(2), 185\u2013194.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eKiani\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eG. R.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1998\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eMarketing opportunities in the digital world\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eInternet Research\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e8\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e2\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e185\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e194\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_033_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac33Aa\\\"\\u003eKiani (1998, p. 192)\\u003c/a\\u003e, \u201c[digital marketing] represents the opportunity to customize the interaction and tailor either the product or the marketing effort to one consumer at a time.\u201d Mass advertising that shows one message to all segments ignores the variation of preferences and tastes in the market.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eIn contrast, segment-based targeting is superior because it aligns the product features with the market segments. The specificity of the target group enables marketers to tailor messages, which results in less wasted ad impressions, as the group\u2019s marketers think are not interested become excluded. Likewise, recommendation mechanisms are optimal when automated and using individual-level data. Note that individual can mean estimates based on conjoint variables (probabilistic methods) instead of using accurate data. However, each visitor is given unique recommendations based on their class. Such approaches are also taken by newsfeed algorithms, such as Facebook\u2019s content ranking algorithm.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eFinally, for strategic planning purposes, such as channel selection, the complexity of individual-level data is excessive. While machine decision-making can handle targeting and recommendation decisions, automating strategic decision-making requires a holistic sense of understanding currently lacking from machine models. Hence, aggregated data representations seem more suitable for strategic decisions, whereas individual data are most optimal in automated decision-making. Whether the personas or numbers-based representations are \u201cbetter\u201d depends on several factors, such as the decision-making style of the individual (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_072_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac72Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eThunholm, P. (2004). Decision-making style: Habit, style or both? \\u003citalic\\u003ePersonality and Individual Differences\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e36\\u003c/italic\\u003e(4), 931\u2013944.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eThunholm\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eP.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2004\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eDecision-making style: Habit, style or both?\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003ePersonality and Individual Differences\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e36\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e4\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e931\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e944\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_072_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac72Aa\\\"\\u003eThunholm, 2004\\u003c/a\\u003e), job role (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eSalminen, J., Guan, K., Nielsen, L., Jung, S., Chowdhury, S. A., \\u0026amp; Jansen, B. J. (2020, July 19). A Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles. \\u003citalic\\u003eIn Proceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/italic\\u003e. In-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"confproc\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSalminen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eGuan\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eK.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eNielsen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eL.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eChowdhury\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. A.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJansen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2020\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003cmonth\\u003eJuly\\u003c/month\\u003e\\u003cday\\u003e19\\u003c/day\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eA Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cconf-name\\u003eProceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/conf-name\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003eSalminen, Liu, Sengun, Santos, Jung, \\u0026amp; Jansen, 2020\\u003c/a\\u003e), and type of task (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eSalminen, J., Guan, K., Nielsen, L., Jung, S., Chowdhury, S. A., \\u0026amp; Jansen, B. J. (2020, July 19). A Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles. \\u003citalic\\u003eIn Proceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/italic\\u003e. In-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"confproc\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSalminen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eGuan\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eK.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eNielsen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eL.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eChowdhury\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. A.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJansen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2020\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003cmonth\\u003eJuly\\u003c/month\\u003e\\u003cday\\u003e19\\u003c/day\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eA Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cconf-name\\u003eProceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/conf-name\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003eSalminen, Jung, Chowdhury, Seng\u00fcn, \\u0026amp; Jansen, 2020\\u003c/a\\u003e). However, the reported empathy benefits of personas should be widely accessible to stakeholders.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e4\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eDiscussion\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe conceptual shift of persona profiles from flat data structures to data-driven personas as interfaces of systems for understanding users opens a completely new era for the implementation of personas. Using these data-driven personas that are embedded as the interfaces to user systems, executives or decision-makers can, for example, provide specific directions for an online marketing campaign, targeting one or more personas. Then, the operational managers can leverage the intermediate analytics information within the data-driven persona systems to refine and target the specific customer segments. Online marketers can then use these refined segments to address the specific customers within these segments that will receive online marketing messages.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_004_s_001_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b3Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e4.1\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eShift to Personalization with Analytics\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eBusiness decision-making is shifting toward more granular use of customer data. The novel method is to apply marketing automation which predicts how individual customers behave; applications include, for example, advertising and email campaigns, product recommendations, and website personalization. The more we are moving toward real-time optimization, the less useful \\u003citalic\\u003ea priori\\u003c/italic\\u003e conceptualizations like target groups and personas become for marketing. This proposition is logically sound since messages and offerings can be even more tailored than in group-based marketing, resulting in efficiency gains.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_004_s_002_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b4Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e4.2\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eShift to Data-driven Personas with the Increased Availability of Online Data\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eGiven that these alternatives are developing at a tremendous pace, the newly established criticism toward personas must be acknowledged and properly addressed. Scholars working with personas cannot simply ignore this important criticism and isolate themselves from it, but they must understand its tenets, address them, and position the use of personas in the light of new developments in the analytics sector. Throughout their existence, personas have been questioned. Yet, they have persistently maintained their appeal, drawing new practitioners and scholars in their sphere of influence. Instead of opting for general defense and justification, we should seek to analyze personas in specific use cases and to objectively assess their strengths and weaknesses. Through such intellectual integrity, HCI and marketing scholars can keep contributing to the development of personas in both theory and practice. Of course, there are many possible cases where one can leverage both manual and automatic methods of persona creation, as discussed in (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_058_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac58Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eSalminen, J., Jansen, B. J., An, J., Kwak, H., \\u0026amp; Jung, S. G. (2018). Are personas done? Evaluating their usefulness in the age of digital analytics. \\u003citalic\\u003ePersona Studies\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e4\\u003c/italic\\u003e(2), 47\u201365.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSalminen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJansen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eAn\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eKwak\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eH.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. G.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2018\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eAre personas done? Evaluating their usefulness in the age of digital analytics\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003ePersona Studies\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e4\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e2\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e47\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e65\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_058_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac58Aa\\\"\\u003eSalminen et al., 2018\\u003c/a\\u003e; \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eSalminen, J., Guan, K., Nielsen, L., Jung, S., Chowdhury, S. A., \\u0026amp; Jansen, B. J. (2020, July 19). A Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles. \\u003citalic\\u003eIn Proceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/italic\\u003e. In-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"confproc\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSalminen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eGuan\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eK.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eNielsen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eL.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eChowdhury\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. A.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJansen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2020\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003cmonth\\u003eJuly\\u003c/month\\u003e\\u003cday\\u003e19\\u003c/day\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eA Template for Data-Driven Personas: Analyzing 31 Quantitatively Oriented Persona Profiles\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cconf-name\\u003eProceedings of the 22nd International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCII\u201920)\\u003c/conf-name\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"comment\\\"\\u003eIn-press.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_057_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac57Aa\\\"\\u003eSalminen et al., 2020\\u003c/a\\u003e).\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_004_s_003_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b5Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e4.3\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eRole of Data-driven Personas in the Age of Analytics\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eNonetheless, our conceptual analysis implies that the claimed irrelevance of personas seems to be mainly based on the disagreement of their advantageous purpose in an age of large-scale customer data. While in certain use cases of digital marketing and online analytics, such as ad targeting and recommendation systems, personas naturally perform poorly against other techniques; there are other use cases where they are superior, simply due to the need for compression of information. Therefore, the usefulness of personas is a question of determining their applicability, defined as the scope of personas. Essentially, when the needs for aggregation range from medium to high, personas become an alternative for data representation. This needed range is illustrated in \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"table\\\" rid=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_005_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b5b3Aa\\\"\\u003eTable 5\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003ctable-wrap id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_tab_005_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b5b3Aa\\\" position=\\\"float\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003eTable 5\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003ccaption\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eLevels of Data Aggregation.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/caption\\u003e\\u003ctable rules=\\\"groups\\\"\\u003e\\u003cthead\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eLevel of aggregation\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eData representation\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003cth align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eExample\\u003c/bold\\u003e\\u003c/th\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/thead\\u003e\\u003ctbody\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eLow\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eIndividual\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eCustomer profiles\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eMedium\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAggregated individual\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003ePersonas\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003ctr\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eHigh\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eAggregated numbers\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003ctd align=\\\"left\\\" valign=\\\"top\\\"\\u003eSegments\\u003c/td\\u003e\\u003c/tr\\u003e\\u003c/tbody\\u003e\\u003c/table\\u003e\\u003ctable-wrap-foot\\u003e\\u003cfn-group\\u003e\\u003cfn\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cbold\\u003eNote:\\u003c/bold\\u003e Aggregated individual data describes personas; keeping individualized attributes while using extensive datasets.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/fn\\u003e\\u003c/fn-group\\u003e\\u003c/table-wrap-foot\\u003e\\u003c/table-wrap\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe concept of personas mirrors the concept of customer orientation in marketing, which has for decades been argued for, specifically in the concepts of marketing orientation (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_046_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac46Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eNarver, J. C., \\u0026amp; Slater, S. F. (1990). The effect of market orientation on business profitability. \\u003citalic\\u003eJournal of Marketing\\u003c/italic\\u003e, 54(4), 20\u201335.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eNarver\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eJ. C.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSlater\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. F.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1990\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eThe effect of market orientation on business profitability\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eJournal of Marketing\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e54\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e4\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e20\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e35\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_046_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac46Aa\\\"\\u003eNarver \\u0026amp; Slater 1990\\u003c/a\\u003e; \\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_034_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac34Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eKohli, A. K., \\u0026amp; Jaworski, B. J. (1990). Market orientation: The construct, research propositions, and managerial implications. \\u003citalic\\u003eJournal of Marketing\\u003c/italic\\u003e, 54(2), 1\u201318.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eKohli\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eA. K.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJaworski\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB. J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e1990\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eMarket orientation: The construct, research propositions, and managerial implications\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eJournal of Marketing\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e54\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e2\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e1\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e18\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_034_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac34Aa\\\"\\u003eKohli \\u0026amp; Jaworski 1990\\u003c/a\\u003e), value co-creation (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_073_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac73Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eVargo, S. L., \\u0026amp; Lusch, R. F. (2008). Service-dominant logic: Continuing the evolution. \\u003citalic\\u003eJournal of the Academy of Marketing Science\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e36\\u003c/italic\\u003e(1), 1\u201310.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eVargo\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eS. L.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eLusch\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eR. F.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2008\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eService-dominant logic: Continuing the evolution\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eJournal of the Academy of Marketing Science\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e36\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e1\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e1\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e10\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_073_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac73Aa\\\"\\u003eVargo \\u0026amp; Lusch, 2008\\u003c/a\\u003e) and customer-dominant logic (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_067_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac67Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eStauss, B., Heinonen, K., Strandvik, T., Mickelsson, K.-J., Edvardsson, B., Sundstr\u00f6m, E., \\u0026amp; Andersson, P. (2010). A customer-dominant logic of service. \\u003citalic\\u003eJournal of Service Management\\u003c/italic\\u003e, \\u003citalic\\u003e21\\u003c/italic\\u003e(4), 531\u2013548.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"journal\\\" publication-format=\\\"print\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eStauss\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eHeinonen\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eK.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eStrandvik\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eT.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eMickelsson\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eK.-J.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eEdvardsson\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eB.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eSundstr\u00f6m\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eE.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eAndersson\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"given-names\\\"\\u003eP.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cyear\\u003e2010\\u003c/year\\u003e\\u003carticle-title\\u003eA customer-dominant logic of service\\u003c/article-title\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"source\\\"\\u003eJournal of Service Management\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cvolume\\u003e21\\u003c/volume\\u003e\\u003cissue\\u003e4\\u003c/issue\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"fpage\\\"\\u003e531\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"lpage\\\"\\u003e548\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003c/span\\u003e' href=\\\"#j_dim-2020-0005_ref_067_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac67Aa\\\"\\u003eStauss, Heinonen, Strandvik, Mickelsson, Edvardsson, Sundstr\u00f6m, \\u0026amp; Andersson, 2010\\u003c/a\\u003e). By influencing the level of motivation and empathy, personas can also influence actions taken by individuals at different organizational levels and, thus, become a vehicle for a higher degree of market orientation within the organization employing them.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\u003c/sec\\u003e\\u003csec id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_s_004_s_004_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab1b3b6Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003clabel\\u003e4.4\\u003c/label\\u003e\\u003cdiv\\u003eScope of Both Personas and Analytics within the Confines of Decision-making\\u003c/div\\u003e\\u003cp\\u003eThe question then becomes: \\u003citalic\\u003eWhat decisions are the individuals making?\\u003c/italic\\u003e Obviously, the answer depends on several factors, notably the industry, organizational context, and the position of the decision-maker. Here, we have based our list of decision tasks in digital marketing. Even in this context, characterized by rapid innovation and technology as a driving force, personas seem to have their role. When dealing with a representation of a person, the interaction between personas and the users of analytics systems becomes evident. The users in these situations often use terms such as \u2018she is interested in...\u201d, \u2018she likes...\u201d. Such verbalization is not usually heard when speaking of data; for numbers, the interpretation tends to be fewer personas (\u201cthey are...,\u201d etc.). The scope forcefully becomes more general and loses the appeal of individual characteristics. The second argument, consequently, is to define the scope of personas, more needs to be known of the decision-makers. As such, there are several areas for future research, as discussed in (\\u003ca data-toggle='tooltip'  ref-type=\\\"bibr\\\" data-tooltip-info='\\u003cspan class=\\\"ref\\\"  id=\\\"j_dim-2020-0005_ref_029_w2aab3b7c26b1b6b1ab2ac29Aa\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"mixed-citation\\\"\\u003eJung, S. G., Salminen, J., An, J., Kwak, H., \\u0026amp; Jansen, B. J. (2018). Automatically Conceptualizing Social Media Analytics Data via Personas. \\u003citalic\\u003eProceedings of the International AAAI Conference on Web and Social Media (ICWSM 2018)\\u003c/italic\\u003e, 715\u2013716.\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"element-citation\\\"  publication-type=\\\"confproc\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"name\\\"\\u003e\\u003cspan class=\\\"surname\\\"\\u003eJung\\u003c/span\\u003e\\u003csp